## Project Structure

- Use App Router (app directory)
- Organize by feature in the app directory: `app/[feature]/page.tsx`
- Place shared components in `components/` directory
- Keep utilities in `utils/` directory
- Store types in `types/` directory or colocate with components
- Store models in `models/` directory

## File Naming Conventions

- Use kebab-case for directories and component files: `user-profile/`, `blog-posts/`
- Use lowercase for utility files: `helpers.ts`, `constants.ts`

## TypeScript

- Always use TypeScript over JavaScript
- Define proper types for props, avoid `any`
- Use interfaces for object shapes, types for unions/intersections

## Component Patterns

- Prefer Server Components by default (no 'use client' unless needed)
- Add 'use client' only when using:
  - useState, useEffect, or other React hooks
  - Event listeners (onClick, onChange, etc.)
  - Browser-only APIs
  - Context providers
- Keep Client Components small and leaf-level when possible
- Use async/await in Server Components for data fetching

## Data Fetching

- Fetch data in Server Components using async/await
- Use native fetch with Next.js automatic caching
- Implement loading.tsx for loading states
- Implement error.tsx for error boundaries
- Use parallel data fetching with Promise.all when possible
- Revalidate data with `revalidatePath` or `revalidateTag`

## Routing

- Use file-based routing in app directory
- Dynamic routes: `[id]/page.tsx` or `[...slug]/page.tsx`
- Route groups: `(auth)/login/page.tsx` for organization without URL segments
- Implement proper metadata exports in page.tsx files

## Styling

- Prefer Tailwind CSS for styling
- Use `cn()` utility (clsx + tailwind-merge) for conditional classes

## Performance

- Optimize images with next/image component
- Use `priority` prop for above-the-fold images
- Implement proper `loading="lazy"` for below-the-fold images
- Use dynamic imports for heavy components: `const Component = dynamic(() => import('./Component'))`
- Implement Suspense boundaries for streaming
- Use Server Actions for mutations instead of API routes when possible

## Server Actions

- Define Server Actions with 'use server' directive
- Place in separate files or at top of Server Components
- Return serializable data only
- Implement proper error handling and validation
- Use `revalidatePath` or `revalidateTag` after mutations

## State Management

- Use React Server Components for server state
- Use URL search params for shareable state
- Use Context for client state that needs to be shared
- Consider Zustand for complex client state
- Avoid prop drilling with composition patterns

## Forms

- Use zod for validation schemas
- Provide clear error messages and field-level errors

## Security

- Sanitize user inputs before displaying
- Use CSRF protection for mutations
- Implement proper authentication checks
- Use Content Security Policy headers
- Keep dependencies updated
- Never expose API keys in client-side code

## Accessibility

- Use semantic HTML elements
- Implement proper ARIA labels when needed
- Ensure keyboard navigation works
- Maintain proper heading hierarchy
- Provide alt text for images
- Test with screen readers
- Ensure sufficient color contrast

## Error Handling

- Implement error.tsx for route-level error boundaries
- Use try-catch in Server Actions and API routes
- Provide user-friendly error messages
- Log errors server-side for debugging
- Implement global error boundary in root layout
- Handle 404s with not-found.tsx

## Code Quality

- Use ESLint with Next.js config
- Format with Prettier
- Use absolute imports with @ alias: `@/components/Button`
- Keep components small and focused (single responsibility)
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks
- Document complex functions with JSDoc comments
- Use meaningful variable and function names

## Git Practices

- Write clear, concise commit messages
- Keep commits atomic and focused
- Use conventional commits format
- Review diffs before committing
- Don't commit .env files or secrets
- Keep package-lock.json or yarn.lock in version control
